message.content: The $y$-intercept of a line is the $y$-coordinate of a point on the line when $x=0$. Therefore, if $(x,y)$ is a point on the line, we have $y=mx+b$ for some slope $m$ and $y$-intercept $b$. If $y=13$ when $x=0$, then $13=0\cdot m+b=b$, so $b=13$. Therefore, the sum of the slope and the $y$-intercept of the line containing both points is $m+b=m+13$.
